<statement>
<p>
Show that <m>\displaystyle\lim_{n\to\infty}1/n^2=0</m>.
</p>
</statement>

<!-- <hint></hint> -->


<answer>
<p>
Given <m>\epsilon \gt 0</m>, we need to find a number <m>N</m> so that whenever <m>n\gt N</m>, we have
<me> \left|\frac{1}{n^2}-0\right|=\frac{1}{n^2} \lt \epsilon. </me>
Rearranging this gives (and using the fact that <m>\epsilon</m> is positive)
<me>
  \frac{1}{\epsilon}\lt n^2
</me>
Taking the square-root of both sides then tells us that we need
<me>
  n \gt \frac{1}{\sqrt{\epsilon}}
</me>
Therefore, we could take <m>N</m> to be any number greater than <m>1/\sqrt{\epsilon}</m>.
In particular, we could take <m>N</m> to be the smallest integer greater than <m>1/\sqrt{\epsilon}</m>, which we denote by
<me> \left\lceil 1/\sqrt{\epsilon} \right\rceil. </me>
</p>
</answer>

<solution>
<proof>
<p>
Let <m>\epsilon \gt 0</m>. Take
<me> N=\left\lceil 1/\sqrt{\epsilon}\right\rceil </me>
Then for <m>n\gt N</m>, we have
<me> \left|\frac{1}{n^2}-0\right|\lt \frac{1}{N^2} \lt \epsilon. </me>
Hence
<me> \lim_{n\to\infty}1/n^2=0. </me>
</p>
</proof>

</solution>
</exercise>
